  "prompt": "Why the colour of wires in homes are black, green and red?",
  "response": "The colors of wires in homes typically follow certain standards to ensure safety and proper identification during electrical installations and repairs. The most common color code for wires in homes within the United States and many other countries is:\n\n1. **Black or Red Wires (Hot/Live Wires):**\n   - These wires carry the electrical current from the power source to the outlet, switch, or other destination.\n   - Black is the most common color for hot wires, but red may also be used, especially in situations where two hot wires are needed (e.g., for a 240-volt circuit).\n\n2. **White or Gray Wires (Neutral Wires):**\n   - Neutral wires return the current to the power source and complete the electrical circuit.\n   - In standard residential electrical systems, neutral wires are typically white.\n\n3. **Green or Bare Wires (Ground Wires):**\n   - Ground wires provide a path for electrical current to safely return to the ground in case of a fault or short circuit, helping to prevent electrical shocks and fires.\n   - They are typically green or bare copper (no insulation).\n\nThe specific colors black, red, and green that you've mentioned may vary based on regional wiring practices and standards:\n- **Black:** as a hot wire\n- **Red:** as an alternative hot wire, especially in multi-way switching configurations or split-phase circuits\n- **Green:** as a ground wire\n\nIt's crucial always to adhere to local wiring codes and regulations, as improper wiring can lead to serious safety hazards. If working on electrical systems, it's recommended to consult with a qualified electrician.",
